Background

In the data folder, you will find data about shark incidents in California between 1950-2022. The data are from: State of California- Shark Incident Database.

Load the libraries

library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

Load the data

Run the following code chunk to import the data. In this chunk, I am removing NAs.

sharks <- 
  read_csv("data/SharkIncidents_1950_2022_220302.csv", 
           na=c("NA", "N/A", "Unknown", "NOT COUNTED", "", " ")) %>% 
  clean_names()

Questions

  1. Are there any hotspots for shark incidents in California? Show the top five counties with the most incidents.
sharks %>% 
  group_by(county) %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  summarise(number_of_incidents = sum(incident_num)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(number_of_incidents)) %>% 
  filter(number_of_incidents > 179)
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   county              number_of_incidents
##   <chr>                             <dbl>
## 1 San Luis Obispo                     404
## 2 Humboldt                            389
## 3 Sonoma                              202
## 4 Santa Cruz                          192
## 5 Island - Santa Rosa                 189


The top five hotspots for shark incidents in California are San Luis Obispo, Humboldt, Sonoma, Santa Cruz, and Santa Rosa Island.
2. Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents per county.

sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = county, y = incident_num, fill = county)) +
  geom_col(na.rm = TRUE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Total Number of Incidents per County",
    x = "County",
    y = "Number of Incidents"
  )

  1. Are there months of the year when incidents are more likely to occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by month. Which month has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = incident_num, fill = month)) +
  geom_col(na.rm = TRUE) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Total Number of Incidents per Month",
    x = "Month",
    y = "Number of Incidents"
  )

  1. Is there a time of day when most attacks occur? Make a plot that shows the total number of incidents by time of day. Which time of day has the highest number of incidents?
sharks %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = time, y = incident_num)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_col()`).


Interestingly, the time of day where the most incidents occur is at 11:30.
